            <h2 class="topic_area_title syndicate">The Basics</h2> 
            <div class="pages"> 
             <div class="page" id="page_57"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">The Basics: <span>Overview</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <p>A bone density test measures how strong&nbsp;bones are. The test will tell you if you have osteoporosis (os-tee-oh-puh-ROH-sis), or weak bones.</p>
               <p>Women are at higher risk for osteoporosis than men, and this risk increases with age.</p>
               <ul>
                <li>If you are a woman age 65 or older, schedule a bone density test.</li>
                <li>If you are a woman age 64 or younger and you have gone through menopause, ask your doctor if you need a bone density&nbsp;test.</li>
               </ul>
               <p>If you are at risk for osteoporosis, your doctor or nurse may recommend you get&nbsp;a bone density test every 2 years.</p>
               <p>Men can get osteoporosis, too. If you are a man over age 65 and you are concerned about your bone strength, talk with your doctor or nurse.&nbsp;</p>
               <h3>What is osteoporosis?</h3>
               <p>Osteoporosis is a bone disease. It means your bones are weak and more likely to break. People with osteoporosis most often break bones in the hip, spine, and wrist.</p>
               <p>There are no signs or symptoms of osteoporosis. You might not know you have the disease until you break a bone. Thats why its so important to get a bone density test to measure your bone strength.&nbsp;</p>
               <h3>What happens during a bone density test?</h3>
               <p>A bone density test is like an x-ray or scan of your body. A bone density test doesnt hurt, and you don't need to do anything to prepare for it. It only takes about 15 minutes.&nbsp;</p>
               <p></p> 
              </div>

             <div class="page" id="page_879"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">The Basics: <span>Am I at Risk?</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <h3>Am I at risk for osteoporosis?</h3>
               <p>Anyone can get osteoporosis, but its most common in older women. The older you are, the greater your risk for osteoporosis.</p>
               <p>These things can also increase your risk for osteoporosis:</p>
               <ul>
                <li>Hormone changes (especially for women who have gone through menopause)</li>
                <li>Not getting enough calcium and Vitamin D</li>
                <li>Taking certain medicines</li>
                <li>Smoking cigarettes or drinking too much alcohol</li>
                <li>Not getting enough physical activity</li>
               </ul>
               <p>Visit these websites to learn more about osteoporosis and bone health:</p>
               <ul>
                <li><a href="http://www.niams.nih.gov/health_info/bone/osteoporosis/osteoporosis_hoh.asp#5" target="_blank">Risk Factors for Osteoporosis</a></li>
                <li><a href="http://www.niams.nih.gov/Health_Info/Bone/osteoporosis/Isabel_story.asp" target="_blank">Isabels Story</a></li>
                <li><a href="http://www.niams.nih.gov/health_info/bone/SGR/surgeon_generals_report.asp" target="_blank">Surgeon Generals Report on Bone Health and Osteoporosis: What it Means to You</a></li>
               </ul> 
              </div> 
              <div id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_0_topic_navigation_1" class="topic_navigation clearfix"> 
               <div class="content_page_navigation clearfix"> 
                <span class="content_page_link right"> <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_0_pageNextLabel_1" class="pageHeading">Next section</span> <a id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_0_pageNext_1" class="button next" href="#the-basics_3">Treatment Options</a> </span>

             <div class="page" id="page_397"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">The Basics: <span>Treatment Options</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <h3>What if I have osteoporosis?</h3>
               <p>If you have osteoporosis, you can still slow down bone loss. Finding and treating this disease early can keep you healthier and more active,&nbsp;lowering your chances of breaking a bone.</p>
               <p>Depending on the results of your bone density test, you may need to:</p>
               <ul>
                <li>Add more calcium and vitamin D to your diet</li>
                <li>Exercise more to strengthen your bones</li>
                <li>Take medicine to stop bone loss</li>
               </ul>
               <p><a href="https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/patientinstructions/000502.htm" target="_blank">Learn about medicines used to treat osteoporosis</a>.</p>
               <p>Your doctor can tell you what steps are right for you. It doesnt matter how old you are  its not too late to build stronger bones.</p> 
              </div>

           <div id="take-action" class="topic_area"> 
            <h2 class="topic_area_title syndicate">Take Action!</h2> 
            <div class="pages"> 
             <div class="page" id="page_59"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">Take Action: <span>Get Tested</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <p>Take these steps to protect your bone health.</p>
               <h3>Schedule a bone density test&nbsp;if your doctor recommends it.</h3>
               <p>Ask your doctor if you are at risk for osteoporosis and find out when to start getting bone density tests.</p>
               <p>Print these <a href="/HealthTopics/Tool.aspx?id=46">questions for the doctor about preventing osteoporosis</a>&nbsp;and take them to your next checkup.</p>
               <h4>What about cost?</h4>
               <p>Screening for osteoporosis is covered under the <a href="https://www.healthcare.gov/health-care-law-protections/" target="_blank">Affordable Care Act</a>, the health care reform law passed in 2010. Depending on your insurance plan, you may be able to get screened at no cost to you.</p>
               <p>Check with your insurance company to find out what's included in your plan. For information about other services that are covered by the Affordable Care Act, <a href="https://www.healthcare.gov/what-are-my-preventive-care-benefits/#part=2" target="_blank">visit&nbsp;HealthCare.gov</a>.</p>
               <p>If you have Medicare, <a href="http://www.medicare.gov/coverage/bone-density.html" target="_blank">find out about Medicare coverage for bone density tests</a>.</p>
               <p>If you dont have health insurance, you can still get a bone density test. To learn more, <a href="https://findahealthcenter.hrsa.gov/" target="_blank"> find a health center near you</a>.</p> 
              </div> 
              <div id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_topic_navigation_0" class="topic_navigation clearfix"> 
               <div class="content_page_navigation clearfix"> 
                <span class="content_page_link right"> <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pageNextLabel_0" class="pageHeading">Next section</span> <a id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pageNext_0" class="button next" href="#take-action_2">Calcium and Vitamin D</a> </span> 
                <span class="content_page_link left"> <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pagePrevLabel_0" class="pageHeading">Previous section</span> <a id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pagePrev_0" class="button previous" href="#the-basics_3">Treatment Options</a> </span> 
                <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pageRange_0" class="content_page_range">4 of 7 sections</span> 
               </div> 
              </div> 
              <!-- /.topic_navigation --> 
             </div> 
             <div class="page" id="page_122"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">Take Action: <span>Calcium and Vitamin D</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <p>You need both vitamin D and calcium for strong bones.</p>
               <h3>Get enough calcium.</h3>
               <p><a href="/HealthTopics/Topic.aspx?id=40">Calcium</a> helps keep your bones strong. Good sources of calcium include:</p>
               <ul>
                <li>Low-fat or fat-free milk, cheese, and yogurt</li>
                <li>Almonds</li>
                <li>Broccoli and greens</li>
                <li>Tofu with added calcium</li>
                <li>Orange juice with added calcium</li>
                <li>Calcium pills</li>
               </ul>
               <p><a href="/HealthTopics/Tool.aspx?id=47">Use this calcium shopping list</a> to help you find foods high in calcium.</p>
               <h3>Get enough vitamin D.</h3>
               <p>Vitamin D helps your body absorb (take in) calcium.</p>
               <p>Your body makes vitamin D when you are out in the sun. You can also get vitamin D from:</p>
               <ul>
                <li>Salmon or tuna</li>
                <li>Fat-free or low-fat milk and yogurt with added vitamin D</li>
                <li>Breakfast cereals and juices with added vitamin D</li>
                <li>Vitamin D pills</li>
               </ul>
               <p><a href="http://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-Consumer/#h2" target="_blank">Find out how much vitamin D you need each day</a>.</p> 
              </div> 
              <div id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_topic_navigation_1" class="topic_navigation clearfix"> 
               <div class="content_page_navigation clearfix"> 
                <span class="content_page_link right"> <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pageNextLabel_1" class="pageHeading">Next section</span> <a id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pageNext_1" class="button next" href="#take-action_3">Get Active</a> </span> 
                <span class="content_page_link left"> <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pagePrevLabel_1" class="pageHeading">Previous section</span> <a id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pagePrev_1" class="button previous" href="#take-action_1">Get Tested</a> </span> 
                <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pageRange_1" class="content_page_range">5 of 7 sections</span> 
               </div> 
              </div> 
              <!-- /.topic_navigation --> 
             </div> 
             <div class="page" id="page_60"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">Take Action: <span>Get Active</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <h3>Get active.</h3>
               <p><a href="/HealthTopics/Topic.aspx?id=22">Physical activity</a> can help slow down bone loss. Weight-bearing activities (like running or doing jumping jacks) help keep your bones strong.</p>
               <ul>
                <li>Aim for 2 hours and 30 minutes a week of moderate aerobic activity. If you are new to exercise, start with 10 minutes of activity at a time.</li>
                <li>Do strengthening activities at least 2 days a week. These include lifting weights or using resistance bands (long rubber strips that stretch).</li>
                <li>Find an exercise buddy or go walking with friends. You will be more likely to stick with it if you exercise with other people.</li>
               </ul>
               <h4>Find activities that work for you.</h4>
               <p>You don't need special equipment or a gym membership to stay active. Check with your local community center or senior center to find fun, low-cost, or free exercise options.</p>
               <ul>
                <li><a href="/HealthTopics/Category/health-conditions-and-diseases/obesity/stay-active-as-you-get-older-quick-tips" target="_self">Use these tips to help you stay active as you get older</a>.</li>
                <li><a href="https://go4life.nia.nih.gov/keep-going-stay-motivated-to-be-active/" target="_blank">Get ideas for staying motivated to be active</a>.</li>
               </ul>
               <p>If you have a health condition or a disability, be as active as you can be. Your doctor can help you choose activities that are right for you.&nbsp;</p> 
              </div> 
              <div id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_topic_navigation_2" class="topic_navigation clearfix"> 
               <div class="content_page_navigation clearfix">

                <span class="content_page_link left"> <span id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pagePrevLabel_2" class="pageHeading">Previous section</span> <a id="content_tabContentRepeater_areaContentRepeater_1_pagePrev_2" class="button previous" href="#take-action_2">Calcium and Vitamin D</a> </span>

             <div class="page" id="page_298"> 
              <h2 class="topic_page_title">Take Action: <span>Healthy Habits</span></h2> 
              <div class="syndicate"> 
               <h3>Stay away from cigarettes and alcohol.</h3>
               <p>Smoking cigarettes and drinking too much alcohol can weaken your bones.</p>
               <ul>
                <li>Learn more about how to <a href="/HealthTopics/Topic.aspx?id=24">quit smoking</a>.</li>
                <li>If you drink alcohol, <a href="/HealthTopics/Topic.aspx?id=16">drink only in moderation</a>. This means no more than 1 drink a day for women and no more than 2 drinks a day for men.</li>
               </ul>
               <h3>Take steps to prevent falls.</h3>
               <p>Falls can be especially serious for people with weak bones. You can make small changes to <a href="/HealthTopics/Topic.aspx?id=17">lower your risk of falling</a>, like doing exercises that improve your balance. For example, try walking backwards or standing up from a sitting position without using your hands.</p> 
              </div>
